CPLN 675 Midterm: Floods

Lechuan Huang

Zihan Zhao

2022-03-29

Motivation

In recent years, heavy rainfall and resulting flooding caused severe damage across Canada, particularly on the west coast. But a new report suggests that rising sea levels due to climate change put Canadians at greater risk of flooding. Disasters caused by flooding are the primary cause of economic losses in eastern Canada.

A recently released flood-related report found that nearly 4.8 million Canadians live within 10 kilometers of the eastern or western coastline and are “likely to be disproportionately affected by climate change-induced flooding,” including rising sea levels, extreme weather events, or changing tidal events.

To minimize the negative impact of flooding on cities in western Canada, we need a new model that effectively predicts flood risk. By summarizing and analyzing the flood forecasting model in eastern cities, we can provide the government with a range of crucial placement areas in the urban area that is more affected by floods. Relevant government departments can also make urban emergency plans before extreme weather and other disasters to reduce disaster costs.

Our goal is to build a flood prediction regression model by collecting and integrating various urban resource data from the Open data websites of the two cities to predict the high-risk areas of flood disasters in future cities. Furthermore, we hope this forecast report will provide helpful suggestions for urban flood control emergency plans and have specific guiding significance for the future urban design of relevant municipal departments and planners.

This model analysis method can comprehensively consider and integrate the current status of various aspects of the city (such as hydrological resources, land use, elevation) and is more comprehensive than other prediction methods. Therefore, the prediction results of this model are more reliable when the dependent variable is properly screened. Because the prediction model will predict the high-risk areas of future flood disasters in the city, it is very instructive for future urban plots’ rezoning and proposed land use. This prediction also helps planners design building density and structural stability more rationally.

We bring various dependent variables into the predictor generated by mapping the prediction model through R. We then compare the high-risk areas of flooding in the generated prediction map with the maps of flooded areas in previous years and the existing urban hydrological map. If our prediction map has a high degree of coincidence with these two maps, our prediction model is more accurate and effective.

Join to the fishnet

We join our predictors into the fishnet. In addition to join the raw data into the fishnet, we also calculate the distance of fishnet block to another related fishnet block.

vars_net <- 
  cbind(elevation_net, tree_net, slopep_net, steep_net, park)%>% 
  mutate(slope=sloper)%>%
  dplyr::select(elevation, tree, slope, steep, park, -cal_dem_ele)%>%
  mutate(uniqueID = rownames(.))

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
    pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

vars_net$steep.nn =
  nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(steepp), 3)

vars_net$tree.nn =
  nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(tree), 3)

vars_net$hydro.nn =
  nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net)), st_coordinates(st_centroid(hydro)), 3)

river_net <- 
  hydro %>% 
  dplyr::select() %>% 
  mutate(river = as.numeric(1)) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, mean) %>%
  mutate(river = ifelse(is.na(river), 0, river))

flood_net <- 
  flood %>% 
  dplyr::select() %>% 
  mutate(flood = as.numeric(1)) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, mean) %>%
  mutate(flood = ifelse(is.na(flood), 0, flood))

final_net <- 
  cbind(vars_net,flood_net)

Model

Firstly, we splite our training set and testing set.

final <- 
  final_net %>%
  mutate(elev = elevation-min(elevation),
         stee = steep/max(steep)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-elevation, -steep,-geometry.1)%>%
  rename(floodm = flood)

set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(y = paste(final$flood), p = .70,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)

finalTrain <- final[ trainIndex,]
finalTest  <- final[-trainIndex,]

Then we build our model using Generalized linear model.

finalModel <- glm(floodm ~ ., 
                  family="binomial"(link="logit"), data = finalTrain %>%
                    as.data.frame() %>%
                    dplyr::select(-geometry,-uniqueID))

summary(finalModel)

When it’s done, we output the predicted probability of a test set fishnet cell being flooded conditional on our model.

classProbs <- predict(finalModel, finalTest, type="response")

testProbs <- data.frame(obs = as.numeric(finalTest$flood),
                        pred = classProbs)

ggplot(testProbs, aes(x = pred, fill=as.factor(obs))) + geom_density() +
  facet_grid(obs ~ .) + xlab("Probability") + geom_vline(xintercept = .5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("dodgerblue4", "darkgreen"),
                    labels = c("Not flooded","Flood"),
                    name = "")

Reflection

For Calgary’s prediction of high-risk flood areas, the dependent variables we consider are slopes, hydrology, elevation, natural preserved land, trees. The prediction map calculated from these dependent variables agrees with previous flood coverage areas. However, for the Edmonton area, the high-risk flood areas on the predicted map calculated by the same dependent variable are primarily affected by the location of urban trees, or there is an inevitable error.

Through our screening of dependent variables, we found that the elevation and distance to rivers and lakes of cities have the greatest impact on the accurate prediction map, so they become the most important factors in our prediction model.

Our prediction is based on integrating existing relevant resources in the city. We comprehensively consider the largest influencing factors of flood flow under extreme weather: elevation and slopes. We also verified the reliability of our prediction model by fitting the ROC curve (0.8737), which proves that this is a more reliable prediction model.

For our prediction model for Edmonton, we felt that the location of trees too influenced the map results. Therefore, in the next step, we need to make some adjustments to this model, remove the dependent variable of tree location or reduce the influence of trees on the entire prediction model.
